    <text>
        <body>
            <div style="handwritten" type="letter" xml:id="d.1">
                <head type="title">Pieter Nanninck to Miklós Oláh (Leuven, 16 July 1537)</head>
                <floatingText type="regesta">
                    <body>
                        <p xml:id="reg.p.1">1. He sent his last letter to Oláh and others with
                            Rutger Pathius, but the lad has not returned, and nobody knows anything
                            about him. If he is with Rutger Ressen, he should tell him off severely;
                            but Nanninck is worried because everything is full of military tents. If
                            he knows anything about the war, he should write him about that, too. 2.
                            He wrote what he thinks about Athila in his previous letter, if it has
                            been lost, he will write it again. He is worried that if Oláh returns
                            home, he will only arrive to another war, and if the court and the Queen
                            do not hold him back, he might even take up arms to fight for getting
                            Hungary back. He only wishes Oláh’s book got published.</p>
                    </body>
                </floatingText>
                <pb/>
                <p xml:id="p.1">Petrus Nannius Nicolao Olao salutem plurimam. </p>
                <p xml:id="p.2">[1.] Ornatissime et Humanissime Patrone! <choice>
                        <orig>Ipsi</orig>
                        <supplied>Ipsis</supplied>
                    </choice> ferme Kalendis Iulii <persName>iuvenem</persName><note type="critic"
                        xml:id="note.1">Rutger Pathius.</note> hinc quendam cum litteris meis<note
                        type="critic" xml:id="note.2">Ep.
                        587.<ref>olahus.tei.15370630_1</ref></note> ad te emandavi, habebat idem
                    litteras ad dominum <persName>Franciscum a Burgundia</persName>,<note
                        type="critic" xml:id="note.3">François de Bourgogne.</note> emiseram autem
                    ad hoc ad dominum <persName>Ruttgerum</persName><note type="critic"
                        xml:id="note.4">Rutger Ressen.</note> (nam tu illius nomine petieras), ut
                    cum eo assidue Latine loqueretur. </p>
                <pb/>
                <p xml:id="p.3">Is nusquam apparet, nec post illius abitum quicquam de ipso
                    audivimus: si est apud dominum <persName>Rutgerum</persName>, castigabis illum
                    verbis, quod nos in hac sollicitudine relinquit, nec quemquam de sua fortuna <choice>
                        <orig>consciunt</orig>
                        <supplied>conscium</supplied>
                    </choice> facit. Nos certe omnia suspectamus, eo, quod omnia militibus, castris,
                    expeditionibus plena sint. Valde anxius sum de illius salute, tu quicquam de
                    illius rebus compertum habes, rogo Tuam Humanitatem, ut mihi illud quam primum
                    significes. Libere apud te ago, sed me docuit tua humanitas, ut fastigium
                    dignitatis tuae non respicerem, si quod hic est de bello, velim mihi significes. </p>
                <p xml:id="p.4">[2.] Scripsi, quod de tuo <hi rend="italic">Athilo</hi> sentirem
                    idque in eis litteris,<note type="critic" xml:id="note.5">Ep.
                            587.<ref>olahus.tei.15370630_1</ref></note> quas hic
                        <persName>iuvenis</persName><note type="critic" xml:id="note.6">Rutger
                        Pathius.</note> ad te pertulit (ut spero), quae si cum iuvene perierint,
                    denuo scribam, sed vero iudicio et ex ipsa animi sententia, ut etiam tunc feci
                    semperque facturus sum. Tu, mi Patrone, rectissime valeas, et id agas, quod
                    Musae, quibus pro tanta eruditione plurimum debes, a te summo iure postularint,
                    hoc est, ut in ipsarum studiis mira, ut soles, felicitate verseres, procul a
                    barbaris castris et sanguinariis et impiis; id mihi eo visum, quia timebam, ne
                    vis animi et spiritus ille Hungaricus te ad aliena bella protruderet, magisque
                    timerem, nisi te aula et regina detinerent, id si unquam futurum est, quod
                    obominor, tum te Hungaria in armis videat ad patriae recuperationem. Habemus
                    Hungariam, modo liber<note type="critic" xml:id="note.7">Sc. <hi rend="italic"
                            >Hungaria</hi>.</note> in publicum exeat, in perpetuum ab oblivionis
                    iniuria vindicatam. Si quid unquam Mars ex studiis tuis post hac occupabit,
                    sperabimus tuo vel consilio, vel armis futurum, ut aliquo modo <milestone
                        unit="pb"/>Christianitatis damnum resarcias. Campus ille tui
                        <persName>Huniadis</persName><note type="critic" xml:id="note.8">John
                        Hunyadi or his son, King Mathias I. On their relatives, see <hi
                            rend="smallcap">Nagy</hi> 2010; <hi rend="smallcap">Nagy</hi> 2021; and
                            <hi rend="smallcap"
                        >Szilágyi–Nagy</hi><?oxy_custom_start type="oxy_content_highlight" color="255,255,0"?>
                        2022<?oxy_custom_end?>.</note><choice>
                        <orig>vittoriis</orig>
                        <supplied>victoriis</supplied>
                    </choice> celebratus te militem et ducem videat, non hic noster Gallicus utrique
                    Christiano madens. Vale, Optime Patrone. </p>
                <p xml:id="p.5">Postridie Iduum <del corresp="Olahus">Iuliarum</del><add
                        corresp="Olahus" type="corr">Iulias</add> 1537.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
